				<hr>
				<p class="lead text-justify text-indent">A recent American study shows that habituating the human brain to mathematical calculations and solving mathematical problems improves people's mental health and fights the symptoms of depression and anxiety. The study was conducted by researchers at Duke University of America, and published its findings in the scientific journal Clinical Psychological Science.</p>
				<p class="lead text-justify text-indent">Researchers analyzed the brain activity of 186 students by MRI, performing certain mathematical operations based on information in their memory. And have found that mathematical process resolution, as a function of memory, stimulates an area in the brain called <span class="font-italic font-weight-bold"> Dorsal Prefrontal Cortex </span>, which is associated with Feelings of depression and anxiety.</p>
				<p class="lead text-justify text-indent">These researchers also found that the intense activity of this area in the brain is associated with decreased symptoms of anxiety and depression in people.</p>
				<p class="lead text-justify text-indent">They said these results will inspire them to develop new strategies to help people regulate their emotions and prevent symptoms of anxiety and depression, particularly in developing countries with anxiety and depression levels. high.</p>
